<br>
I took my discomfort and concern to the nuns in a honest attempt to stabilize my shaken faith, asking them the insoluble questions I could not answer.  They could offer nothing but regurgitated platitudes.  I was asked not to return the following year.  <br>
<br>
I left it alone for a long time and went along living my life, still a xian and just ignoring what I could not solve, but nagged by it at the back of my mind.  It wasn't until I held my newborn daughter in my arms and considered all the things facing me as a responsible and loving parent that I started to think about it again.  A year later, within six months of each other both my parents died and a few months after that my son was born.<br>
<br>
Now the search began in earnest.  I started reading, questioning and debating.  Ultimately, I could not deny, there is no evidence in support of god's existence.  There are reams and reams of evidence against it.  Yeah, I would love for there to be a divine all-father to watch over us.  I wish I could see my Mom again when I die.  I want my Dad to have met his grandson and seen his pride at what his youngest accomplished in life.  My daughter is 5 and she wants a unicorn pegasus too.  We all have romantic wishes and dreams.  However, there is an objective reality, and no matter what we 'believe' or how strongly we wish it, that doesn't make it so.<br>
 <p>DBC67<br>
