<br>
No, I will never see my parents again.  I will see the echo of my fathers smile in my son's happy face, and the shadow of my mother in my daughter's eyes, but I will never see the people who raised me again.  They are gone after long, difficult and victorious lives.  <br>
<br>
My mom beat cancer for 19 years after being told she had a year to live.  My dad overcame a lifetime of abuse and alcoholism to raise his family and put us out in the world as strong, capable individuals.  They were amazing and wonderful people and it was very painful to lose them.  I would not cheapen that pain (it's depth is a reflection of the depth of love felt for them) or their memories by pretending they 'just went someplace else'; or that either of their battles was just wasted effort since they were only stalling some BS salvation and eternal bliss. <br>
<br>
I asked before how the concept of heaven differs from Elysium, Valhalla, Nirvana, or any of the other identical and much older versions of the same thing in different religions.  Yet we can dismiss those as mythology and still pretend the xian one isn't just as much childish fancy.<br>
<br>
I loved them, and they are gone.<br>
     Sad?  Yes.<br>
     Honest?  Yes.<br>
